# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: acidobacteriia
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The genes coding for it are referred to as **16S rRNA genes** and are used in reconstructing phylogenies, due to the slow rates of evolution of this region of the gene.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Fox were two of the people who pioneered the use of 16S rRNA in phylogenetics in 1977.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Multiple sequences of the 16S rRNA gene can exist within a single bacterium.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The descriptor *16S* refers to the size of these ribosomal subunits as reflected indirectly by the speed at which they sediment when samples are centrifuged.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The 16S rRNA gene is used for phylogenetic studies as it is highly conserved between different species of bacteria and archaea.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Carl Woese pioneered this use of 16S rRNA in 1977.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] It is suggested that 16S rRNA gene can be used as a reliable molecular clock because 16S rRNA sequences from distantly related bacterial lineages are shown to have similar functionalities.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Some thermophilic archaea (e.g. order Thermoproteales) contain 16S rRNA gene introns that are located in highly conserved regions and can impact the annealing of "universal" primers.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Mitochondrial and chloroplastic rRNA are also amplified.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The most common primer pair was devised by Weisburg *et al.* (1991) and is currently referred to as 27F and 1492R; however, for some applications shorter amplicons may be necessary, for example for 454 sequencing with titanium chemistry the primer pair 27F-534R covering V1 to V3.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The two primers are almost identical, but 27F has an M instead of a C.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] AGAGTTTGATC**M**TGGCTCAG compared with 8F.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] In addition to highly conserved primer binding sites, 16S rRNA gene sequences contain hypervariable regions that can provide species-specific signature sequences useful for identification of bacteria.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] As a result, 16S rRNA gene sequencing has become prevalent in medical microbiology as a rapid and cheap alternative to phenotypic methods of bacterial identification.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Although it was originally used to identify bacteria, 16S sequencing was subsequently found to be capable of reclassifying bacteria into completely new species, or even genera.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] It has also been used to describe new species that have never been successfully cultured.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] With third-generation sequencing coming to many labs, simultaneous identification of thousands of 16S rRNA sequences is possible within hours, allowing metagenomic studies, for example of gut flora.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] In samples collected from patients with confirmed infections, 16S rRNA next-generation sequencing (NGS) demonstrated enhanced detection in 40% of cases compared to traditional culture methods; moreover, pre-sampling antibiotic consumption did not significantly affect the sensitivity of 16S NGS.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The bacterial 16S gene contains nine hypervariable regions (V1–V9), ranging from about 30 to 100 base pairs long, that are involved in the secondary structure of the small ribosomal subunit.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The degree of conservation varies widely between hypervariable regions, with more conserved regions correlating to higher-level taxonomy and less conserved regions to lower levels, such as genus and species.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] While the entire 16S sequence allows for comparison of all hypervariable regions, at approximately 1,500 base pairs long it can be prohibitively expensive for studies seeking to identify or characterize diverse bacterial communities.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] These studies commonly utilize the Illumina platform, which produces reads at rates 50-fold and 12,000-fold less expensive than 454 pyrosequencing and Sanger sequencing, respectively.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] While cheaper and allowing for deeper community coverage, Illumina sequencing only produces reads 75–250 base pairs long (up to 300 base pairs with Illumina MiSeq), and has no established protocol for reliably assembling the full gene in community samples.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Full hypervariable regions can be assembled from a single Illumina run, however, making them ideal targets for the platform.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] While 16S hypervariable regions can vary dramatically between bacteria, the 16S gene as a whole maintains greater length homogeneity than its eukaryotic counterpart (18S ribosomal RNA), which can make alignments easier.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Additionally, the 16S gene contains highly conserved sequences between hypervariable regions, enabling the design of universal primers that can reliably produce the same sections of the 16S sequence across different taxa.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Although no hypervariable region can accurately classify all bacteria from domain to species, some can reliably predict specific taxonomic levels.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Many community studies select semi-conserved hypervariable regions like the V4 for this reason, as it can provide resolution at the phylum level as accurately as the full 16S gene.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] While lesser-conserved regions struggle to classify new species when higher order taxonomy is unknown, they are often used to detect the presence of specific pathogens.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] In one study by Chakravorty et al. in 2007, the authors characterized the V1–V8 regions of a variety of pathogens in order to determine which hypervariable regions would be most useful to include for disease-specific and broad assays.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Amongst other findings, they noted that the V3 region was best at identifying the genus for all pathogens tested, and that V6 was the most accurate at differentiating species between all CDC-watched pathogens tested, including anthrax.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] While 16S hypervariable region analysis is a powerful tool for bacterial taxonomic studies, it struggles to differentiate between closely related species.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] In the families *Enterobacteriaceae*, *Clostridiaceae*, and *Peptostreptococcaceae*, species can share up to 99% sequence similarity across the full 16S gene.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] As a result, the V4 sequences can differ by only a few nucleotides, leaving reference databases unable to reliably classify these bacteria at lower taxonomic levels.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] By limiting 16S analysis to select hypervariable regions, these studies can fail to observe differences in closely related taxa and group them into single taxonomic units, therefore underestimating the total diversity of the sample.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Furthermore, bacterial genomes can house multiple 16S genes, with the V1, V2, and V6 regions containing the greatest intraspecies diversity.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] While not the most precise method of classifying bacterial species, analysis of the hypervariable regions remains one of the most useful tools available to bacterial community studies.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Under the assumption that evolution is driven by vertical transmission, 16S rRNA genes have long been believed to be species-specific, and infallible as genetic markers inferring phylogenetic relationships among prokaryotes.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] However, a growing number of observations suggest the occurrence of horizontal transfer of these genes.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] In addition to observations of natural occurrence, transferability of these genes is supported experimentally using a specialized *Escherichia coli* genetic system.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Using a null mutant of *E. coli* as host, growth of the mutant strain was shown to be complemented by foreign 16S rRNA genes that were phylogenetically distinct from *E. coli* at the phylum level.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Such functional compatibility was also seen in *Thermus thermophilus*.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Furthermore, in *T. thermophilus*, both complete and partial gene transfer was observed.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Partial transfer resulted in spontaneous generation of apparently random chimera between host and foreign bacterial genes.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Thus, 16S rRNA genes may have evolved through multiple mechanisms, including vertical inheritance and horizontal gene transfer; the frequency of the latter may be much higher than previously thought.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The 16S rRNA gene is used as the standard for classification and identification of microbes, because it is present in most microbes and shows proper changes.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Type strains of 16S rRNA gene sequences for most bacteria and archaea are available on public databases, such as NCBI.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] However, the quality of the sequences found on these databases is often not validated.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Therefore, secondary databases that collect only 16S rRNA sequences are widely used.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] SILVA provides comprehensive, quality checked and regularly updated datasets of aligned small (16S/18S, SSU) and large subunit (23S/28S, LSU) ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences for all three domains of life as well as a suite of search, primer-design and alignment tools (Bacteria, Archaea and Eukarya).
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] GreenGenes is a quality controlled, comprehensive 16S rRNA gene reference database and taxonomy based on a *de novo* phylogeny that provides standard operational taxonomic unit sets.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] EzBioCloud database, formerly known as EzTaxon, consists of a complete hierarchical taxonomic system containing 62,988 bacteria and archaea species/phylotypes which includes 15,290 valid published names as of September 2018.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Based on the phylogenetic relationship such as maximum-likelihood and OrthoANI, all species/subspecies are represented by at least one 16S rRNA gene sequence.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The EzBioCloud database is systematically curated and updated regularly which also includes novel candidate species.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Moreover, the website provides bioinformatics tools such as ANI calculator, ContEst16S and 16S rRNA DB for QIIME and Mothur pipeline.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] MIMt is a compact non-redundant 16S database for a rapid metagenomic samples identification.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] It is composed of 48,749 full 16S sequences belonging to 24,626 well classified bacteria and archaea species.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] All sequences were obtained from complete genomes deposited in NCBI and for each of the sequences full taxonomic hierarchy is provided.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] It contains no redundancy, so only one representative for each species was considered avoiding same sequences from different strains, isolates or pathovars resulting in a very fast tool for microorganisms identification, compatible with any classification software (QIIME, Mothur, DADA, etc).
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The Ribosomal Database Project (RDP) was a curated database that offers ribosome data along with related programs and services.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The offerings included phylogenetically ordered alignments of ribosomal RNA (rRNA) sequences, derived phylogenetic trees, rRNA secondary structure diagrams and various software packages for handling, analyzing and displaying alignments and trees.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] Due to its large size the RDP database is often used as the basis for bioinformatic tool development and creating manually curated databases.
[src:acidobacteriia/16s-rrna] The RDP server was taken offline in 2023, but the software is still available for download.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidimicrobiia] The ***Acidimicrobiia*** are a class of Actinomycetota, in which three families, eight genera, and nine species have been described, *Acidimicrobium ferrooxidans* is the type species of the order.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidimicrobiia] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature (LPSN) and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriaceae] The **Acidobacteriaceae** are a family of Acidobacteriota.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriaceae] The currently accepted taxonomy is based on the List of Prokaryotic names with Standing in Nomenclature and National Center for Biotechnology Information (NCBI).
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriia] The "**Acidobacteriia**" is a class of Acidobacteriota.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriia] Numbered orders do not yet have any cultured representatives.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Members of this phylum are physiologically diverse, and can be found in a variety of environments including soil, decomposing wood, hot springs, oceans, caves, and metal-contaminated soils.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] The members of this phylum are particularly abundant in soil habitats representing up to 52% of the total bacterial community.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Environmental factors such as pH and nutrients have been seen to drive Acidobacteriota dynamics.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Many Acidobacteriota are acidophilic, including the first described member of the phylum, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] There is much that is unknown about Acidobacteria both in their form and function.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Thus, this is a growing field of microbiology.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Some of this uncertainty can be attributed to the difficulty with which these bacteria are grown in the laboratory.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] There has been recent success in propagation by using low concentrations of nutrients in combination with high amounts of CO2, yet, progress is still quite slow.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] These new methods have only allowed approximately 30% of subdivisions to have species documented.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Additionally, many of the samples sequenced do not have taxonomic names as they have not yet been fully characterized.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] This area of study is a very current topic, and scientific understanding is expected to grow and change as new information comes to light.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Other notable species are *Holophaga foetida*, *Geothrix fermentans*, *Acanthopleuribacter pedis* and *Bryobacter aggregatus*.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Since they have only recently been discovered and the large majority have not been cultured, the ecology and metabolism of these bacteria is not well understood.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] However, these bacteria may be an important contributor to ecosystems, since they are particularly abundant within soils.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivisions 1, 4, and 6 are found to be particularly abundant in soils.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] As well as their natural soil habitat, unclassified subdivision 2 Acidobacteriota have also been identified as a contaminant of DNA extraction kit reagents, which may lead to their erroneous appearance in microbiota or metagenomic datasets.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 have been found to dominate in low pH conditions.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Additionally, Acidobacteriota from acid mine drainage have been found to be more adapted to acidic pH conditions (pH 2–3) compared to Acidobacteriota from soils, potentially due to cell specialization and enzyme stability.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] The G+C content of Acidobacteria genomes are consistent within their subdivisions - above 60% for group V fragments and roughly 10% lower for group III fragments.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] The majority of Acidobacteriota are considered aerobes.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] There are some Acidobacteriota that are considered anaerobes within subdivision 8 and subdivision 23.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] It has been found that some strains of Acidobacteriota originating from soils have the genomic potential to respire oxygen at atmospheric and sub-atmospheric concentrations.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Members of the *Acidobacteriota* phylum have been considered oligotrophic bacteria due to high abundances in low organic carbon environments.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] However, the variation in this phylum may indicate that they may not have the same ecological strategy.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] The first species, *Acidobacterium capsulatum*, of this phylum was discovered in 1991.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] However, Acidobacteriota were not recognized as a distinct clade until 1997, and were not recognized as a phylum until 2012.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] In an effort to further classify Acidobacteria, 16S rRNA gene regions were sequenced from many different strains.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] These sequences lead to the formation of subdivisions within the phyla.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Today, there are 26 accepted subdivisions recognized in the Ribosomal Database Project.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Much of this variety comes from populations of acidobacteria found in soils contaminated with uranium.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Therefore, most of the known species in this phyla are concentrated in a few of the subdivisions, the largest being #1.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Most of these microbes are aerobes, and they are all heterotrophic.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Subdivision 1 contains 11 of the known genera in addition to the majority of the species that have been able to be cultivated thus far.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Within the 22 known genera, there are 40 conclusive species.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] The genera are divided amongst subdivisions 3, 4, 8, 10, 23, and 1.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] As the Acidobateria are a developing area of microbiology, it is hypothesized that these numbers will change drastically with further study.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Some members of subdivision 1 are able to use D-glucose, D-xylose, and lactose as carbon sources, but are unable to use fucose or sorbose.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 1 also contain enzymes such as galactosidases used in the breakdown of sugars.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Members of subdivision 4 have been found to use chitin as a carbon source.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Despite the presence of genetic information generally known to encode for carbohydrate processing machinery in various genera of Acidobacteria, several experimental studies have demonstrated the inability to break down various polysaccharides.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Cellulose is the main component of plant cell walls and a seemingly opportune resource for carbon.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] However, only a single species across all subdivisions has been shown to process it, *Telmactobacter bradus* from subvision 1.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Researchers believe that an additional factor in the lack of understanding of carbon degradation by acidobacteria may stem from the present limited ability to provide adequate cultivation conditions.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] To study the natural behavior of these bacteria, they must grow and live in a controlled, observable environment.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] If such a habitat cannot be provided, recorded data cannot reliably report on the activity of the microbes in question.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Therefore, the inconsistencies between genome sequence based predictions and observed carbon processes may be explained by present study methods.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] There has been no clear evidence that Acidobacteriota are involved in nitrogen-cycle processes such as nitrification, denitrification, or nitrogen fixation.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] However, *Geothrix fermantans* was shown to be able to reduce nitrate and contained the norB gene.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] The NorB gene was also identified in *Koribacter verstailis* and *Solibacter usitatus*.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] In addition, the presence of the nirA gene has been observed in members of subdivision 1.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Additionally, to date, all genomes have been described to directly uptake ammonium via ammonium channel transporter family genes.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidobacteriota] Acidobacteriota can use both inorganic and organic nitrogen as their nitrogen sources.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Acidulidesulfobacteriota are ecologically significant in biogeochemical cycling, especially with respect to sulfur and iron.
[src:acidobacteriia/acidulidesulfobacteriota] Their genomes show evidence of interaction with viruses, which can influence host metabolic functions including folate biosynthesis and sulfur pathways.
